{"query": "To control Crassula helmsii, how do chemical methods like herbicides compare in effectiveness to physical methods like using lightproof barriers or salt water?", "summary": "Chemical methods for controlling Crassula helmsii show variable effectiveness. Glyphosate has shown some success, with seven studies finding it reduced C. helmsii, and one study reporting a 98% reduction when glyphosate was combined with diquat (Action 1279). Three out of four studies found that diquat or diquat alginate reduced cover or eradicated submerged C. helmsii, while one study found no effect (Action 1279). Combination chemical approaches were effective, with one study showing that covering C. helmsii with carpet followed by glyphosate treatment killed 80% of the plant (Action 1313).

Physical methods show high effectiveness rates. Seawater treatment demonstrated complete success, with two replicated controlled container trials and two before-and-after field trials finding that seawater eradicated Crassula helmsii (Action 1288). Lightproof barriers using black sheeting or carpet strips also showed strong results, with five before-and-after studies finding they eradicated or severely reduced C. helmsii cover, though progressive recolonization occurred at two sites where initial eradication was reported (Action 1294).

Chemical herbicides like dichlobenil and terbutryne showed only partial effectiveness, with dichlobenil leading to partial biomass reduction in container trials but no effect in field studies, and terbutryne providing partial reduction in submerged C. helmsii (Action 1279). No evidence was found for the effectiveness of manual/mechanical control or dredging, or for draining waterbodies (Actions 1278, 1303).", "action_ids": ["1279","1288","1294","1313","1278","1303"]}

